    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-06-29T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-06-29T10:00:00-05:00" n="482"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d482">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_CFM1">CFM</gloss> lot M 88, box 169, “<persName
                        corresp="#p_CHURCHILLWS1">Churchill</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_EDENA1"
                        >Eden</persName> Visit”</note>
                <head>No. 482<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Assistant Secretary of State for European
                        Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_MERCHANTLT1">Merchant</persName>) of a
                        Meeting of President <persName corresp="#p_EISENHOWER1"
                            >Eisenhower</persName> and Prime Minister <persName
                            corresp="#p_CHURCHILLWS1">Churchill</persName> at the White House, June
                        29, 1954, 11 a.m.</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d482fn1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CHURCHILLWS1">Churchill</persName>arrived at 11 a.m.
                        and he and the President were joined by the others around 11:30; for another
                        account of this conversation, see the entry from <persName
                            corresp="#p_HAGERTYJC1">Hagerty</persName>’s diary, <hi rend="italic"
                            >infra</hi>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                        <lb/>CEV <gloss target="#t_MC1">MC</gloss>–8</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1954-06-29T11:00:00-04:00">June 29, 1954, 11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>Participants:</head>
                    <item>The President</item>
                    <item>Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_CHURCHILLWS1">Churchill</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Dulles</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_EDENA1">Eden</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_MAKINSSRM1">Makins</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CACCIASHA1">Sir Harold Caccia</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BOWIERR1">Bowie</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MERCHANTLT1">Merchant</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>[Here follows a list of subjects discussed.]</p>
                <pb facs="1171" n="1123" xml:id="pg_1123"/>
                <p>The meeting was primarily concerned with the final drafting changes of the
                    declaration subsequently signed and issued by the President and the Prime
                        Minister.<note n="2" xml:id="d482fn2">
                        <ref target="#d488">Document 488</ref>.</note> Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_CHURCHILLWS1">Churchill</persName> made available the cable he
                    had received overnight from the Cabinet in which the only point of substance
                    raised was the reference to “self determination”. After a little discussion the
                    President accepted <persName corresp="#p_CHURCHILLWS1">Sir Winston</persName>’s
                    proposed change in the phrase to refer only to “self government”.</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_EDENA1">Eden</persName> raised with Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_CHURCHILLWS1">Churchill</persName> the suggestion made by Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Dulles</persName> that Thorneycroft come
                    over to Washington this week-end to discuss East-West trade problems with
                    Governor <persName corresp="#p_STASSENHE1">Stassen</persName>.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d482fn3">This suggestion was made at the meeting in <persName
                            corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Dulles</persName>’ office earlier that morning;
                        see CEV <gloss target="#t_MC1">MC</gloss>–7, <hi rend="italic"
                        >supra</hi>.</note> The Prime Minister approved this recommendation and the
                    President telephoned Mr. <persName corresp="#p_STASSENHE1">Stassen</persName> to
                    inform him of this approval and to say the British would issue an announcement
                    on the subject from London.</p>
                <p>It was confirmed by Mr. <persName corresp="#p_EDENA1">Eden</persName> that the
                    Prime Minister had now approved the agreed minutes on Egypt, Germany and the
                    establishment of a working group on Southeast Asian matters.<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d482fn4">See <ref target="#d484">Documents 484</ref>–<ref
                            target="#d486">486</ref>.</note> He also said that they approved the
                    joint instructions to the British and American Ambassadors in Paris in the
                    revised form worked out the afternoon before.<note n="5" xml:id="d482fn5">See
                            <ref target="#d487">Document 487</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>During the course of the meeting Mr. <persName corresp="#p_EDENA1"
                        >Eden</persName> requested the Secretary’s assistance in the matter of
                    releasing certain blocked dollar balances of British firms in China desirous of
                    closing down and bringing their British personnel home. He said that this
                    required a special Treasury license which he understood had from time to time
                    been granted to American firms in a similar predicament. Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Dulles</persName> said that he had no knowledge of
                    this matter but that he would look into it and see what if anything could be
                    done.</p>
            </div>
